maleprepro_text: I was raised to believe that a man is someone who dedicates himself to causes greater than himself. Whether this be through his family, community, church, local government etc. A man is concerned with the direction of his community and uses his position in society to foster a sense of purpose through service in the next generation. All the while, a man must simultaneously nurture and promote his own and the next generation's physical prowess and competitiveness to help develop goal oriented young men and women who are focused on building and maintaining the social fabric of society.
reman_text: If a man wants to be a real man he need to be involved in a cause bigger than oneself. This could be from feeding the homeless to tutoring or coaching underprivileged youth on a more emotional and compassionate end of a scale all the way to fire  or military service on the other  more physical and self sacrificing end of a scale. Neither is truly "better" than another, it is just about figuring out who you are, where your skills are, and how you can best serve the community.

There has, however, been recent developments where more unmanly behaviour is being considered gender-neutral and becoming more acceptable.    Examples of such 'unmanly behaviours include:  Manscaping... This is any behaviour that regards looking after your body is a stylised fashion. Getting manicures and/or pedicures. Trimming or shaving body hair (e.g. underarms, nose, etc), for purely aesthetic purposes.    Doing anything that's target audience is another gender... Whether it is romance novels, women's magazines, 'chick flicks'. Men are often considered unmanly for engaging in such activities.    Yoga. While men are stereotypically depicted as being more physically fit than females, yoga is often considered a form of exercise and fitness that is directed towards women.
